1. Defensive Educational Open Use

Permission is granted, free of charge, to use, copy, study, modify, merge,
publish, distribute, sublicense, and share copies of the licensed material for
defensive cybersecurity education, fraud-awareness training, classroom
simulation, abuse-prevention learning, supervised student projects, and
public-interest defensive experimentation, subject to the conditions below.

2. Attribution

Redistributions must preserve this license text, copyright notices, maintainer
attribution, ORCID attribution when present, and project-level NOTICE,
DISCLAIMER, SAFETY, and SECURITY files when provided.

3. Defensive Purpose Boundary

SECL-covered material is provided for teaching, prevention, review support,
simulation, defensive analysis, and supervised learning. It is not provided for
offensive attack, intrusion, credential theft, fraud, impersonation, evasion,
exploit automation, unsafe surveillance, or criminal automation.

4. Modification And Forks

You may modify and fork the licensed material. Modified copies must not imply
that they are the official maintained school or cybersecurity-training version
unless the changes have been accepted through the official project review
process.

Private modified copies, broken forks, unsafe rewrites, unsupported provider
routes, and local adaptations are the responsibility of the person or
organization maintaining those copies.

5. School Support Boundary

The official maintained school version is supported only when changes are made
through reviewed project channels such as pull requests, maintainer-approved
patches, or other documented review processes.

6. Misuse Responsibility

Misuse of the licensed material is solely the responsibility of the person or
organization performing, directing, deploying, or permitting that misuse.

The license does not create an obligation for Jean-Sebastien Beaulieu,
SecuredMe, OpenAI, Google, Gemini, Antigravity, Codex, contributors, schools, or
reviewers to repair private modified copies, unsafe deployments, illegal
deployments, or harmful workflows.

7. No Authority Transfer

Educational cybersecurity outputs from SECL-covered projects are review support
only unless a qualified human authority independently validates and accepts
them. The licensed material does not make legal findings, diagnoses, regulatory
decisions, enforcement decisions, identity claims, compliance certifications, or
autonomous accusations.

